Trade for firearm(s) Had to put in the rifles category 

 Can be 1 firearm or multiple worth $5,500

 Installed Options

 Original Black Honeycomb Wheels ~ but the alloy 5 Star Rims you see in one of the photos also go with the car. The black rims now also have the original FIERO Centercap. It is silver with the black bird and looks perfect. I just have not taken a photo of that yet but it really makes it perfect. 

 New Tires (Less than 200 miles)

 5 Speed
 Leather Seats (Perfect shape!)

 Air Conditioning ~ Is new air conditioning and is ICE COLD. 

 CD Changer 
 Rear Window Defroster 
 AM/FM Stereo 
 Brand new ($110) Battery that has not been installed yet as the car is in storage.

 Leather Seats ~ Most Fieros do not have the leather and this leather is perfect....no rips or tears like I see on some of these other lower end fieros. 

 Oh and both headlights work perfectly. 

 Power Door Locks 
 Power Mirrors 

 Power Windows 

 Sunroof/Moonroof 
 Tilt Wheel 

 I recently added a brand new original stock leather shifter knob (was $60) and it feels amazing. But the shifter knob you see in the photo is also available if you want it. 

 Seller's Description and Comments

 This 1987 Fiero GT is in amazing condition. Rebuilt engine ~ it drives great and has much more power than your average Fiero. The body is flawless and the original paint is good for its age (you can see in the pictures how reflective the paint still is as it is reflecting the trees in the back ground and even the white lines from the parking lot). The motor runs and sounds great (as perfect as this car looks, the engine is the gem of the car). I am the type of person who is skeptic of any after market work done to any car I buy, especially of an engine that has been re-done. This car was not re-done because it was broken down....it was redone to make it better than your average Fiero and done right. I took it in to Gaynor's Automotive (A premium Shop here in Vancouver) and they actually opened it up and did a complete inpsection and said whoever did this engine did it right, and the car sounds like it! It is a 2800 V6 bored 30-over with forged pistons with a 5 speed transmission. It has roller rocker arms, a crane cam shaft, ported-heads, and a Holley Fuel Injection System. A new cat converter was installed so it passed with flying colors through WA DEQ which cost me $700. I looked for the perfect Fiero for almost 2 years and found this one in Detroit in 2010. The only time this car has ever been driven in the rain was when I drove it home from Detroit, and it drove great! It is currently licensed in WA State. It has a K&N Air Filter and custom dual-quad exhaust. The odometer reads 130,827 but the previous owner rebuilt the engine about 43,000 miles ago. He also did all of the modifications listed above. 

 It has been kept in my garage since 2010 and the previous owner owned thi car since the early 90s and babied it more than his kids. From the time he owned it and as long as I have, it has always been garage kept. The clutch and plugs were recently replaced and have less than 250 miles on them. The car has 4 wheel disc brakes. The front brakes have been checked and look great. The calipers in the rear are new along with the pads and one of the rotors. It has leather interior that is in great shape. The head lights are fully functional. It has Fiero-GT floor mats, and a 10 disc CD-changer. It also has the huge sun roof shown in the pictures. I have nearly all of the paperwork for the car from the early 90s until now. This Fiero is garaged (and covered) and has been meticulously cared for. 

 And you will not have to worry about this car having body cracks or such issues that I have seen recenlty on another fiero here on Craigslist that was in this price range. Can't beleive someone is selling for about my price for their fiero (with low miles) with cracks?? Just because it has lower miles does not mean it is nicer. The air condiitoning is perfect and ice cold ~ and brand new.....have receipts. 

 If you drove one of these gowing up, you know how fun they are...and if you have not yet, you are truly missing out. 

 I have over 10k into this car since 2010 and have receipts. 

 We can meet at my FFL Dealer in Vancouver if we make a deal.

title: For Sale:  BREAKING NEWS:Small Victories "No" Band SS109 M855
postcontent:
Small Victories Pave the Way for Big Wins...
BY TIM SCHMIDT - USCCA FOUNDER
Tim Schmidt
Although it might be a little too early for responsible gun owners like you and me to celebrateâespecially with claims that President Obama "remains committed to 'common-sense' gun regulations"âwe can at least appreciate a small victory this week as the ATF backs off its proposed ban of M855 ammunition.

The Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives announced that, after receiving more than 80,000 comments on the proposalâincluding overwhelming criticism from pro-gun groups and Congressional Republicans, it will NOT ban the commonly used cartridge "at this time."

According to The Hill, "Democrats and gun control groups blasted the move, accusing the administration of caving."

But Josh Earnest, the White House's press secretary, reiterated Wednesday that "the president's commitment to putting in place common-sense rules that will protect Second Amendment rights, but also prevent those who shouldn't have firearms from getting them, is as strong as ever."

I don't think it's too far of a stretch to say that President Obama (among others) doesn't seem to recognize or respect the difference between bad guys with guns and lawful concealed carry permit holders.

I can't think of any other reason why he continues to push for increased regulations on firearms and ammunition, despite evidence that it only deters the law-abiding from being able to rightfully defend themselves and their loved ones.

By now, you and I both know that there will always be people fighting just as hard against the things we believe in as we are fighting for them. (Of course, it doesn't help that the mainstream media never shines light on our side of things.)

But we can't allow the "other side" to define this fight. We can't let their inability to see the truth overshadow what is really happening across the country. And this week, there are a lot of good things happening:

Take Iowa, for example, where the House passed a bill that "would prohibit the public from accessing the names of those who hold permits to carry guns and purchase some weaponsârecords that are currently open to the public."

And what about Tennessee, where "the Senate Judiciary Committee approved measures to allow guns in parks, guns in trunks of cars parked at schools or universities, guns at property used by but not owned by schools, and targets that explode"?

And let's not forget about Florida, where the House and Senate have already passed a "bill to allow concealed firearms on the state's college and university campuses."

This is just a small slice of positive gun-related news taking place in this great country as we speak (Utah, Arizona, West Virginia, and several other states are also moving forward with their own pro-gun measures). We should continue to recognize such efforts. Remember, small victories pave the way for big wins.

Remember what Margaret Mead once said? "Never doubt that a small group of thoughtful, committed citizens can change the world; indeed, it is the only thing that ever has."

We're on the right path. Let's continue to get involved, to speak up, and to fight back. The latest backtrack by the ATF is proof that it all really does matter.

Take Care and Stay Safe,

For Sale is a used Front Firing ASI - UZI Blank Firing Gun 9MM PAK with 50 Rounds of Blank Ammo.  This was used as a movie prop and is no longer needed.  It has been fired approximately 25 to 30 times and has had about 400 rounds through it.

The EKOL ASI is a full-size replica of the classic UZI Machine gun. This Front firing model UZI employs blank firing technology that was previously unavailable in the United States. It Fires from the front of the Barrel expelling flames and Smokes from the FRONT of the barrel creating the Muzzle flash many people prefer. This Front Firing Blank Firing Fully Automatic ASI UZI fires 15 9MMPAK gun powder charged blanks in 1.9 Seconds. It comes with a 15 Round Magazine. Modes of operation are: 

1. Safety, it will not fire on safety 
2. Semi-Automatic, means it fires ejects and reloads automatically every time you press and release the trigger 
3. Fully Automatic means that it fires ejects and reloads automatically and continuously as long as you press and just hold down the trigger. It does not stop firing until you let up on the trigger or run out of ammunition when it is in fully automatic mode, like a machine gun. 

It is easy to move the switch for the 3 modes. This is a great theatrical or film/movie prop UZI Blank firing machine gun. It is great to just have fun with and it is approved by the ATF that it fires blanks only, can not fire or be converted to fire a projectile (bullets) and there is no license of any type required for purchase this blank firing gun.

title: For Sale:  Lyman TargetSpot 10X Serial 4436 Mint Condition
postcontent: Lyman TargetSpot. This scope is one of the first target scopes made by Lyman. The first TargetSpots were introduced in 1934 in 8x and 10x . This scope predates first Unertls by 3 years. With serial number of 4436 must have been made 1934/5. Equipped with Bausch & Lomb lenses the TargetSpot had 1.125 objective lens, adjustable for parallax and adjustable ocular lens. Lyman micrometer 1/4 click adjustments and .0007 in fine crosshairs. This scope did not come in a woooden box those came several years later with the Super TargetSpot. I do not have the original cardboad box. The paint on the objective index marks are perfect with no hand oil stains, Same with windage and elevation knobs. There are no screw driver marks anywhere. Finish is 99.9%. Lenses are clear and perfect. It is a pleasure to look thru this scope. It is obvious this scope was used very little if at all and most likely stored in a climate controlled space. Not a single speck of rust.

title: For Sale:  WWII, Nazi-era, 9mm Belgium occupation FN High Power Semi-Automatic Pistol
postcontent:
FN 9mm
A WWII, Nazi-era, Belgium occupation FN High Power Semi-Automatic Pistol in 9MM with black leather flap holster and extra commercial magazine. This 1940's vintage predecessor to the current Browning High Power has the following features: 4 3/4 inch round barrel, blued metal finish, rounded front blade sight, fixed-notch rear sight, serrated ring hammer, smooth trigger, and checkered plastic grips. Metal stampings include: left side of slide -- three line maker mark, address and Browning Patent reference on the left side of the slide -- FABRIQUE NATIONALE D'ARMES DE GUERRE (NATIONAL FACTORY OF ARMS FOR WAR) HERSTAL-BELGIQUE (HERSTAL, BELGIUM) BROWNING'S PATENT DEPOSE -- along with the Nazi Eagle over WaA 140 and the Nazi Eagle over a circled swastika; left side frame - the Nazi Eagle over WaA 140 and the Nazi Eagle over a circled swastika; right side of slide, frame and barrel -- the serial number 31955 f; front of slide beneath muzzle -- the Nazi Eagle over WaA 140; magazine rear wall -- the Nazi Eagle over WaA 140. Condition is original and very good with an estimated 90% of the blued finish on all metal surfaces. Bluing is toning to brown/grey patina on the grip straps. Edge wear. Scattered handling marks. Grips are very good with some scratches. Leather holster has a mild scuffs and surface cracks from age, as expected and the brown leather color is showing through the light brown finish in some areas. Mechanically, this pistol is very good to excellent. Serial number: 31955f. A collectible pistol from WWII that demonstrates the Belgian manufacturing characteristics under Nazi Germany occupation and control.

The FN P35 âHi-Powerâ had been in production since 1935. Designed by John Moses Browning, and completed by Dieudonne Saive, the pistol was chambered in 9mm and had a 13 round capacity thus called âHigh Powerâ, and was a desirable military firearm. For comparison, the German issued P.08 Luger and P.38 held 8 rounds of 9mm each. When the German forces invaded and occupied Belgium in 1940, they also took over the FN (Fabrique Nationale, in Herstal Belgium) plant.

The Hi-Power was immediately liked by the Germans, and reassigned the designation Pistole 640(b)

The pre-war inventories of parts at the FN were used to produce more of the Pistole 640(b), all bearing Nazi Waffenamts and the typical swastika-eagle stamps.
 When in early â42 the pre-war inventories ran out, the German led war-production was started up, and most Hi-Powers after that had wooden grips, unlike the synthetic grips used on prior production guns.

This pistol has a WaA140 waffenamt in it, which indicates it was produced in Belgium between 1942 and 1944 and inspected by the Wehrmacht inspectors in Luttich, Belgium.
That Hi-Power is known as the third (and final) sub-variation of the German occupation pistol designated the P.640b.

Those brown plastic resin grips are original to that gun as are the rather roughly machined and finished major parts. The blue finish on the b suffix pistols was thin to say the least.
The abbreviated serial numbers on the barrel and slide were common practice for Hi-Powers produced in that time frame.
Unmarked aluminum follower magazines are also correct for guns in this serial range.

Serials up to 63,000b in the b suffix when the Germans had to fall back to the East out of Belgium in September of 1944.
No fixed dates of manufacture are around that I am aware of. Stands to reason that this one was made in the latter half of 1944.

Good looking correct supple holster that does not look either over oiled or dried out. 
It is best for the finish of the gun to not store it in the holster where rust has a better chance to develop or gun oil that would stain the leather and stitching.

In my experience the plastic grip 3rds are more rare to encounter than the much more common wood gripped, fixed sight variation Hi-Powers. I say this as a result of my research of this gun and itâs history

The majority of WWII Hi-Powers, due in large part to their popularity with shooters, have been shot and handled to the point of large degrees of finish being lost.
This gun does not seem to have that apply as the front grip finish is the first thing to go on the Hi-Power and this one looks like the gun would rate in the high 90s for condition.

This 1944 vintage predecessor to the current Browning High Power has the following features: 4 3/4 inch round barrel, blued metal finish, rounded front blade sight, fixed-notch rear sight, serrated ring hammer, smooth trigger, and checkered plastic grips.
